Vernon Jordan, who grew up in public housing and became a prominent figure in American politics, civil rights, and business, passed away. He dedicated his life to fighting for civil rights and economic justice, and was known for his wise counsel to presidents and business leaders. Despite facing adversity, including being shot by a white supremacist, Jordan remained committed to creating a more equitable America. He believed that although progress had been made, there was still work to be done in dismantling systemic racism and injustice. To honor his legacy, it is important to continue the fight for equality. Jordan's passing is described as a loss of a great leader, leaving a void that will be deeply felt. Condolences are extended to his family.